    <p> The path there went through beautiful dense forest and bush landscape. Always with a view of the second volcano. After eating, we were even lucky that the clouds on the volcano were almost completely disappeared and we still got photos of the second volcano in full size. Only the third refused to come out of the clouds throughout the day. </p>
    <p> After a few last photos we made our way to Wanganui. The road there led us through the level before we drove through a mountain landscapes covered with meadows. Sheep pastures as far as the eye can see. The first time I saw sheep in New Zealand. Before that, I only passed cattle farms. When we arrived in Wanganui, we decided to drive to the paid campsite, as the free one lay directly on a railway line and was somehow not nice. </p>
    <p> The way to the other campsite led through an industrial area and then through a somewhat dilapidated area. When I arrived at the campsite, I asked the Lord at the reception whether the whole city looks like this or whether there was a nicer city center somewhere. He showed us on a card and told us what else could be done. We may decide to take a look at the next day. What we experienced in Wanganui the next day I'll tell you tomorrow. </p>
